properties.Title: Flood Warning Being Issued For The Lakes Within Whiteshell Provincial Park
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a Flood Warning for the Whiteshell Lakes due to increased precipitation in the area. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as levels and flows are rising. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing water or waters of unknown depth. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-15T15:15:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-10-14T15:18:42-05:00, 06B94699-130D-D341-6D83-169EB45A42CE
Area: Whiteshell Provincial Park
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Near blizzard conditions have been experienced in Resolute today. It is expected that as the winds gradually ease this evening and the snow moves out of the area, the visibility will improve. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-15T05:29:01-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-14T19:37:01-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0362559429.2019
Area: Resolute

properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Elevated pollution levels are expected or occurring. AIR QUALITY ADVISORY IN EFFECT FOR GOLDEN The Ministry of Environment & Climate Change Strategy in collaboration with the Interior Health Authority has issued an Air Quality Advisory for Golden due to high concentrations of fine particulate matter that are expected to persist until weather conditions change. Persons with chronic underlying medical conditions should postpone strenuous exercise until the advisory is lifted. If you are experiencing symptoms such as continuing eye or throat irritation, chest discomfort, shortness of breath, cough or wheezing, follow the advice of your health care provider. Staying indoors helps to reduce fine particulate exposure. Exposure is particularly a concern for infants, the elderly and those who have diabetes, and lung or heart disease. ### For more information on current air quality, visit www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/environment/air-land-water/air. Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
Expires: 2019-10-15T07:48:10-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, the B.C. Ministry of Environment, 2019-10-14T15:49:10-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2279836242.2019
Area: East Columbia

properties.Title: Frost Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Frost may damage some crops in frost-prone areas. Temperatures will drop slightly under the freezing mark tonight over some areas north of the St. Lawrence River. ### Frost advisories are issued when temperatures are expected to reach the freezing mark during the growing season, leading to potential damage and destruction to plants and crops. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An area of high pressure building over the Mackenzie River Basin and an intense low pressure system approaching the Gulf of Alaska will produce blizzard conditions along the Dempster Highway near the Richardson mountains. Easterly winds of 80 km/h will develop Tuesday morning and persist until late Wednesday morning. The strong winds, light falling snow and existing snow pack will combine to reduce visibilities for the period. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-15T15:12:36-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-14T23:13:36-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0475435952.2019
Area: Dempster

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. A strong Pacific frontal system will track across Haida Gwaii tonight and move inland on Tuesday. Rain at times heavy will begin tonight and continue through Tuesday. Rainfall amounts up to 60 mm can be expected by Tuesday evening. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. A strong Pacific frontal system will slowly track across northern British Columbia giving 10 to 20 cm of snow to the Cassiar Mountains. The snow will begin this evening and intensify by Tuesday morning. Snow will taper off Tuesday evening with flurries persisting until Wednesday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

Area: Cassiar Mountains

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A strong frontal system will move across Haida Gwaii tonight. Ahead of the front, southeast winds 80 to 100 km/h over Haida Gwaii will continue tonight and ease Tuesday morning. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
